ln the prologue to the three books ol odes Horace expresses the modest hope that Maecenas will count him a lyric poet; in the epi· logne, he triumphantly declares that he has built a monument of verse that will outlast bronze and unnumbered time itself. He boasts that his fame shall grow when heis dead, and that so long as Rome shall last, men shall say that he was the first to transplant Aeolian verse to Italy. So let the Muse place the laurel crown upon his brow.

lt is little wonder that when Horace surveyed the substantial body of lyric verse which he was about to intnrst to the world, he felt a nat· ural pride in his accomplishment. This feeling was undoubtedly in- creased by the thought of his humble origin and by the memory of his early struggles for recognition and of the envious scorn he had aroused among the noble poetasters of his day. Ol this last, however, there is no hint in this ode. Horace now knew that his fame was secure. He was the first Roman to write a large amount of lyric poetry‚ and his odes had already received the lavorable judgment of the best critics in Rome. -Il to our modern laste he seems too frank in expression, we must remember that antiquity apparently took no such offense, sor he had many predecessors, and later poets did not hesitate to speak with equal boldness.
